Admission Information
Admission Date: 2023-02-22
Discharge Date: 2023-02-25

Discharge Diagnoses
Acute on chronic hypoxic respiratory failure
COPD exacerbation
Obstructive sleep apnea
BPH
Hypertension
Tobacco use
Chronic diastolic congestive heart failure

Patient is a 71-year-old male with a history of COPD-on 3 to 4 L of oxygen at home, hypertension, chronic diastolic congestive heart failure, BPH, obstructive sleep apnea-CPAP dependent, presented to the ER with complaints of shortness of breath. Patient was found to have acute exacerbation of COPD, acute on chronic hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to the same, he was initially placed on BiPAP, later on weaned off to nasal cannula. He was started on steroids, breathing treatments, respiratory status improved significantly with the same, patient was initially in stepdown unit,
Transferred to the floor. All of his other home medications were resumed.
Patient mentions that he has been having trouble with fixing his CPAP at home, requested him to call the CPAP company for assistance.
Also to follow-up with pulmonology.
This morning, he was examined at bedside, no acute events overnight, patient will be discharged home today in stable condition, recommended to follow-up with pulmonology, medication compliance.
